Rafe tensed. Matthis clenched his jaw. The skeletons did not stumble or wander. Shoulder to shoulder, they stepped around Matthis and Rafe. Rafe exhaled. Matthis narrowed his eyes.

Each deliberate step touched the mud without a squelch and lifted again without a stain. Pristine, white bones drifted through the square. A group of children playing a game in an alley halted the game. Their leather ball fell. Their faces paled. They scurried away like roaches from light and peeked around corners and through door cracks. The skeletons did not stop or react. Empty sockets forward, they proceeded one step after another. The street echoed Matthis's and Rafe's footsteps. 

One man in a dusty black cap emerged onto a narrow street with his pickaxe slung behind his neck, the flat end curled around his shoulder and tucked safely into his armpit. In a single file, the skeletons drifted around him. The man jumped and swung his pickaxe. The skeleton nearest him exploded. He dropped the haft from shaky hands. He backed away and stumbled into a wall. Rafe laid a hand on the man's shoulder. The struck skeleton lay in bone fragments scattered across the dirt street. The others did not break stride. They simply split around the pair, like water around rocks.

Matthis gasped. The fragments reassembled themselves. He stopped to watch. Rafe stood beside him. Pieces flew through the air and reattached themselves. Joints locked into place. Ribs slipped into the spine. The complete skeleton resumed its silent march as though nothing had happened. Rafe and Matthis looked at each other. The man, his mouth open, pulled his pickaxe out of the mud. Not a single skull moved to look back. 

The skeletons glided around a corner past the carpenter's shop. Through a window, Matthis spotted Mercy talking to the carpenter's wife. Mercy halted her conversation. Her eyebrows rose. She bared her teeth. She rushed to the shop door and flung it open. She watched the procession slide up the street. Matthis locked eyes with her. She glowered. He looked away.

The shop long behind them, Matthis checked over his shoulder and surveyed the street. Mercy stalked them, her eyes shadowed. She whispered to anyone who poked a head around their doors or windows. A group slowly formed around her. Several scowled at Matthis. One man bared his brown teeth. Matthis saw the flash of kitchen knives. Many carried pickaxes.  

Heads ducked out of windows and doors, which slammed shut. A woman with a baby in her arms squeaked and rushed to cover her child with her body and scrambled around a corner. Three men outside the apothecary fell to their knees. 

A man in a spotless, dustless white robe, whom Matthis had never seen, sat atop a sleek, muscular horse and spoke to Bartholomew and Godric. The man's head snapped forward and watched the procession, arms folded and resting on the horse's neck, face hard. Bartholomew gaped, and his arms circled his middle. Godric steadied himself on a wall.

Nine skeletons crested the cemetery hill, followed by Matthis and Rafe. A group trailed behind them, headed by Mercy. A dull glint shone from gray headstones, once coal-dusted, now rain-washed. 